# 6. Publishing

Publishing SHALL be non-blocking.

The Publisher SHALL NOT know which services subscribe.

The Publisher SHALL continue execution immediately after successful publication.

---

# 7. Subscription

Services subscribe using Event Type.

Example:

```go id="s0j6me"
Subscribe(TaskCompleted, handler)

Subscribe(BundleInstalled, handler)

Subscribe(ValidationCompleted, handler)
```

Subscribers SHALL remain independent.

---

# 8. Event Ordering

Events published by a single Publisher SHALL preserve publication order.

Ordering between independent Publishers is not guaranteed.

Every Event SHALL contain a monotonically increasing local Sequence Number.

---

# 9. Correlation

Related Events SHALL share a CorrelationID.

Example:

```text id="f0e0xw"
TaskQueued

↓

TaskStarted

↓

UsageRecorded

↓

TaskCompleted
```

All four Events reference the same CorrelationID.

---

# 10. Reliability

The Internal Event Bus provides at-most-once delivery.

Events are not persisted.

Missed Events SHALL NOT be replayed.

Persistent audit history belongs to dedicated storage components.

---

# 11. Error Handling

Subscriber failures SHALL NOT affect the Publisher.

Subscriber failures SHALL NOT prevent delivery to other Subscribers.

Every subscriber failure SHALL generate:

```text id="hn8mgi"
SubscriberError
```

---

# 12. Thread Safety

The Event Bus SHALL support concurrent Publishers.

The Event Bus SHALL support concurrent Subscribers.

Implementation SHALL be lock-safe.

---

# 13. Service Isolation

Services SHALL communicate only through:

* public interfaces;
* Internal Event Bus.

Direct service-to-service calls SHALL be minimized.

---

# 14. Data Ownership Rule

Services own their state.

Services publish Events.

Other services consume Events.

No service SHALL directly modify another service's persistence.

Cross-service database access is prohibited.

---

# 15. Design Invariants

Invariant 1

Events are immutable.

---

Invariant 2

Publishers never know Subscribers.

---

Invariant 3

Subscribers never modify Events.

---

Invariant 4

The Event Bus owns no business logic.

---

Invariant 5

The Event Bus is not persistent.

---

Invariant 6

Network communication is outside the scope of the Event Bus.

---

Invariant 7

Services synchronize through Events rather than shared persistence.
